element.documentation:
"For each project, the Site Managers have different starting points for doing scheduling and our reporting setup will be varying from project to project.
And because this is not supported and captured by any system, then we are unable to analyse how many hours it takes to perform tasks throughout our work flow, so we cannot see where to focus our efforts in improving existing ways of working; this is i.e. within areas of LEAN, supplier negotioations, feeding back lessons learned to VPS about design implications affecting excess time spent on installing certain components"

"We miss out on having a precise and up-to-date plan which leaves us vulnerable in terms of:
(1) forecasting the project execution timeline including key milestones driving payments (financial performance KPI's such as cash flow) and (2) leaves us with an information flow relying on people's best ability instead of systems supporting the sharing of information to key stakeholders (PM team, Finance Controller, Resource Management (utilisation rates) and individually assigned project employees not knowing for how long the project will take)"

"Communication lines between entities are not working properly meaning we risk receiving information too late which affects our ability to plan and prepare the NCR work that we might need to execute during the Construction phase.
When informed too late, it will be adding extra cost to executing the NCR/CIM scope as the cost increases the further into the Construction stages we get (from ground - to after WTGs have beeb erected, and if offshore, then even more expensive)"

"Because we do not have this standardised process, the existing systems do not support us in: (1) capturing the time spent on executing unshcduled work, (2) the purchasing of needed materials/parts for such work and (3) ensure traceability of what was done during the Construction scope. "

Construction cannot get the associated costs re-imbursed. Even if we start within the deadline, we spend too much admin time by NCR Coordinators to chase the re-imbursement. This results in Construction project appearing more costly than they actually were.

"Consequence is that it requires a lot of manual work from Site personnel to create NCRs on each WTG instead of adding WTGs to the same overall NCR.
Another consequence is that we risk that locations get missed out to have work done meaning we have to sometimes fix it later in the process after WTGs have been erected.
We often see on Pre-Installation that all NCR work is booked on one location instead of spread out on several locations becuase it is too time-consuming to spread out hours spent on actual locations."

"Because we cannot generate the needed paperwork for customs clearance when wanting to return the defect component, we sometimes have to return these items meaning we are not always legally compliant.
Construction has to sell the defect component to the enitity in Vestas which will receive and repair it, but because components are either not created or enriched, we cannot process this type of cost re-imbursement adding extra costs to a project "

It means Construction cannot deliver correct documentation to either Service or to the Customer affecting the quality of the product we deliver and potentially also affecting payment milestones as the Customer will hold back payments until we have lived up to contractual obligations which affects cash flow.

The pain point for site management is that we need to manyally consider/assess weather data throughout the scheduling of a project meaning our predictability/forecasting on executing the work is not data-driven and thereby often more inaccurate because it is up to the individual to apply such factors to the schedule

Because overall ressource overviews and their planned activities are dis-connected from a site scedule with progress element, then Site Management cannot see how their ressource demands can be affected over time and also, the site progress is not transparent to resource departments responsible for allocating sufficient resources to sites.

"Becaue of this, it is not always clear to Site Managers how they should prioritise work on site when they create and maintain their site schedules.And if they do find these deadlines from the schedule, then we are still at risk of human error potentially missing an important deadline that the system could have highlighted to us. Also, because the Project Schedule (P6) and the Site Schedule are not inter-connected and thereby reflecting progress and reaching milestones (or not reaching milestones within agreed deadline), we lose transparency about actual deadlines agreed with Customers and we don't capture data to support or document potential discussions about claims or LDs "

"We miss out on having data to support the analysis of external's performance on our projects understanding how much time was spent on certain activities in the work flow.
This affects our ability to re-negotiate agreements with suppliers and also gain insights on where in our work flow to start improvement initiatives"

This means we miss out on creating a plan with exact same basic structure and thereby also enabling us to capture how much time was spent on certain activities if we not manually record such data and manully enter the data into some "database" allowing us to share and compare data across projects
If there is not allignment across regions then we cannot analyze how many hours were spent on certain categories of work to understand how this is affecting the project performance

The consequence of this wrong format is that we cannot share properly with Customer and it is the resources on site who needs to understand the information about their next assignment.
We then have to create an Excel sheet which is time-consuming.
It is also not possible to trace back to see what happened on certain dates which can be needed for i.e. Customer- or Supplier-related disputes

"We miss out on understanding how much was actually consumed and thereby understanding the actual costs in each project. We usually often end up with excess consumables at the end of a project and we cannot return the items because they are not created in the system It also prevents us to collaborate between ""neighbouring"" projects where we could support each other with sending excess materials/parts "
This makes it hard to add external ressource profiles to planned locations (i.e. WTG's) and capturing the time they spend on executing the work they are assigned to.

"The pain point is Construction cannot deliver correct documentation to either Service or to the Customer. It can lead to Vestas being unable to meet billing milestones resulting in a less profitable project.
This can lead to service technicians being sent back to the WTGs to retrieve lost information which leads to excess costs."

Construction ends with a major pain point when unable to complete As Built documentation before handing over to Customer as final payments cannot be made before we have delivered our part of the agreement.

Because we are unable to automatically generate a Customer-oriented Daily Progress Reports, we spend extra admin time to put together a DPR that lives up to the expectations from our Customers.
Another important factor is that the data is not captured and summarised, so we can use it for analysis to understand performance and where we should focus on improving

"Because the quality of our data is poor we have a hard time:
(1) To generate sufficient DPRs to the Offshore Customer as part of the contractual terms & obligations
(2) To support claiming extention of time related to delays like waiting on client to energise a string or waiting on weather
(3) To analyse on internal performance measurement to distinguish on how many hours spent on contractual work and how much was on quality issues categoriesedunder i.e. NCR or CIM
(4) To supporrt the work of Contract Mgrs, as they need data to support claims on extention of time. There is a set date for each activity listed in the contract, so if we exceed, then the Contract Mgr can drive the claim process if the Customer is responsible for the delay. We wouldn't be able to do so, if we didn't have time stamps coming from people recording time
(5) Providing sufficient feedback on quality issues as this is supported by these data to demonstrate what costs we have spent on which activities
"

"After FOI, there is no shared view of allocated people. Site Managers create a site specific ressource plan and if changes happen to the allocated people when people are swapped, covered during holidays or training. We find out too late that they might not have the right certifcates or site inductions are not planned causing delays in the plan. A lot of these small incidents accumulate to inefficiency either becuase we have too few or too many resources in certain periods of time.
Quality of planning: If we had clear visibility of skills of the resources, then we can plan better with combining teams and who should do which tasks. Sometimes, we find out that the plans made by the Site Managers are not matching the people's experience and training, and we find out too late"

Because we don't have an easy-to-share solution with all site personnel, we are lacking "one source of truth" about what needs to happen and who needs to do what communicated in a clear and visually strong format

"Because of this, we manually confirm through e-mails, or through SharePoint files, so back office can perform goods received in SAP.
This leaves us in risk of human error negatively affecting the transparency, documentation and payment flows."

"The communication flows related to hours spent are happening outside any Vestas system (i.e. SAP), and because we do not have an approval flow supported by any system we have to manually enter hours spent. Those hours are currently only used for reporting on KPI ""Total Recordable Injury Rate"" (TRIR) and not used for the time spent on task allowing us to analyse on how to improve our performance"

We have to manually inform document controller to get as is updated, but there is a risk of human error here and also, we quickly move on to next task on site, so details related to completed work can be forgotten to be maintained because these information is not required to be registered by a system when closing the work on a location

"It generates a lot of time consumption to reflect updates, as we cannot synchronise Actual Data (site progress) with planned activities. Furthermore, we cannot extract important information such as: - performance (dashboard) - updated planning "
